"Ta, ta!" exclaimed the good man, shaking his gray head;
                        "we must reason with the child. Let go his leg, daughter, I will
                        vouch for him; eh, Jean?"

"I'll return in a minute or two," she called back
                        from a region which Pre Beret well knew was that of the pantry;
                        "don't get impatient and go away!"

"Promise me that you will not taste liquor this night,"
                        Father Beret went on, grasping the young man's arm more firmly;
                        "promise me, my son, promise me."

"J'm'porte trs bien, merci,
                            Mo'sieu Ren," was the quick response;
                            "et vous?"

"It's time to change the subject," she said;
                        "tell me what you have seen while away. I wish I could go far off
                        and see things. Have you been to Detroit, Quebec, Montreal?"

"Pardon me, Mademoiselle; forgive me, I beg of you," he
                        exclaimed, earnestly modulating his voice to sincerest beseechment;
                        "I really did not mean to be impudent, nor"

"We must try it over again some day soon," he said;
                        "I find that you can show me a few points. Where did you learn to
                        fence so admirably? Is Monsieur Roussillon your master?"

"You made it and set it up," he lightly remarked;
                        "you must see that no enemy ever gets possession of it, especially
                        the English."

"If she'd give up that flag I'd let her
                        go," said Hamilton. "I hate like the devil to confine her;
                        it looks brutal, and makes me feel like a tyrant."

"What's the diff'ence?" he demanded.
                        "I'd jest as soon be kicked now as arter while;
                        it's got to come anyhow."

It was the sing-song voice used by Father Beret in his sermons and prayers;
                        but something went with it indescribably touching. Farnsworth felt a lump
                        rise in his throat and his eyes were redy to show tears.

Farnsworth ground his teeth and swore; but Father Beret appeared not to hear;
                        he bit deep into a scone, took a liberal sip of the muddy red wine and
                        added:

"Gentlemen," said Helm, with an impressive oath,
                        "that is Clark's soldiers, and they will take your fort;
                        but they ought not to have spoiled this apple toddy!"
